Filtering groups — Spark's having equivalent.

In sequel, when you want to keep only the groups that satisfy some condition on an aggregate — say, customers with more than five approved transactions — you use the having clause. It filters after the grouping, on the aggregated values.

The dataframe API has no having keyword. But you do not need one, because the equivalent is simply to chain a filter after the aggregate. You group, you aggregate to produce your measure with an alias, and then you filter on that aliased column. That filter, applied to the post-aggregation result, is your having.

The reason this works cleanly is the order of operations. The filter sees the already-computed aggregate columns, so you can compare against the count, or the sum, or whatever you produced. It reads naturally top to bottom — group, aggregate, then filter the groups.

So the mental translation to remember is direct. A where clause filters rows before grouping. A having clause filters groups after aggregating. In the dataframe API, the first is a filter before the group-by, and the second is a filter after the aggregate. Same two filters, placed on either side of the grouping.
